  "local_port": 37060,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the appropriate way to use Ms., Mrs., and Miss?",
  "response": "The titles **Ms.**, **Mrs.**, and **Miss** are honorifics used in English to address or refer to women. They convey information about a woman's marital status or provide a neutral form of address. Understanding the appropriate usage of each can ensure respectful and accurate communication. Here's a breakdown of each title:\n\n### 1. Ms. ([miz])\n\n- **Usage:** **Ms.** is a neutral title that does not indicate marital status. It is widely used when a woman's marital status is unknown, irrelevant, or when she prefers not to disclose it.\n- **Pronunciation:** Pronounced \"miz.\"\n- **Example:** *Ms. Johnson will be joining us for the meeting.*\n\n- **When to Use:**\n  - When addressing women in professional settings.\n  - When the marital status is unknown or should not be assumed.\n  - If a woman explicitly prefers \"Ms.\"\n\n### 2. Mrs. ([missiz])\n\n- **Usage:** **Mrs.** indicates that the woman is married. It is traditionally followed by the husband's full surname, but many women now use it with their own first name or full name.\n- **Pronunciation:** Often pronounced \"missiz.\"\n- **Example:** *Mrs. Smith is the CEO of the company.*\n\n- **When to Use:**\n  - When you know the woman is married and she prefers this title.\n  - In formal contexts where traditional titles are customary.\n\n- **Note:** Some married women may choose to retain their maiden name while still using \"Mrs.\"\n\n### 3. Miss ([mis])\n\n- **Usage:** **Miss** traditionally refers to an unmarried woman or girl. It is typically used for younger women or when marital status is known to be unmarried.\n- **Pronunciation:** Pronounced \"mis.\"\n- **Example:** *Miss Davis, could you please come to the front?*\n\n- **When to Use:**\n  - When addressing girls or unmarried women.\n  - In formal contexts where the distinction between married and unmarried is customary.\n\n### **Choosing the Appropriate Title**\n\n- **Respect Preferences:** Always consider an individual's preferred title. If unsure, \"Ms.\" is generally a safe and respectful default.\n- **Professional Settings:** In business or professional communications, \"Ms.\" is commonly preferred to maintain neutrality.\n- **Formal Correspondence:** Use the title that aligns with the recipient's known preference or marital status, if relevant.\n- **Addressing Envelopes:** Follow any specific guidelines provided by the individual or organization.\n\n### **Examples in Context**\n\n- **Formal Letter Salutation:**\n  - *Dear Ms. Thompson,*\n  - *Dear Mrs. Anderson,*\n  - *Dear Miss Lee,*\n\n- **Informal Context:**\n  - In casual interactions, it's often acceptable to use first names without any title, unless a title is specifically requested or culturally expected.\n\n### **Modern Considerations**\n\n- **Gender Neutrality:** \"Ms.\" is increasingly favored for its neutrality, especially in professional and public contexts.\n- **Personal Choice:** Some women may prefer to use their first name only, omitting any title.\n- **Cultural Variations:** Usage can vary based on cultural norms and personal preferences, so it's respectful to follow the lead of the individual being addressed.\n\n### **Summary**\n\n- **Use \"Ms.\"** as a neutral, default title regardless of marital status.\n- **Use \"Mrs.\"** for married women who prefer this designation.\n- **Use \"Miss\"** for unmarried women or girls, or when it's culturally appropriate.\n\nWhen in doubt, opting for \"Ms.\" is typically respectful and appropriate in most situations.",
